    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-119">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-119" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-119">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-119">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-119" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-119" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Proposition: there is no meta-rationality. There are only people who have integrated the possibility of self-deception into their stories about themselves, and are more careful to listen to all sides than average. But they are no more likely to arrive at the truth than anyone else.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-120">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-120" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-120">
http://elidourado.com/                <span id="dsq-author-user-120">Eli Dourado</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-120" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-120" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I think you&#8217;re getting carried away. People who have integrated the possibility of self-deception are more likely to arrive at the truth.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-3" id="dsq-comment-121">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-121" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-121">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-121">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-121" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-121" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Counter story: people are innately horrible at arriving at the truth, and to the extent that we ever get there it&#8217;s because of larger social systems that have good feedback mechanisms for weeding out the crap and rewarding the good stuff.</p>
<p>If the above story is true (open to debate), then believing that awareness of self-deception improves an individual&#8217;s probability of accuracy may just be another form of self-deception. They may be no better off than people who buy into specific priors wholeheartedly and without question; in both cases it&#8217;s the larger system that takes their points of view as inputs that matters.</p>
<p>I believe there&#8217;s a Boettke paper along these lines, but having trouble finding it.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-4" id="dsq-comment-123">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-123" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-123">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-123">Brock_C</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-123" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-123" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>You can test this theory fairly easily, I think. Do people who behave as if they can be wrong arrive at conclusions eventually adopted by others at a higher rate than the self-confident?</p>
<p>Or you could test children for personality, and then see how good they are at re-discovering answers we already know are correct.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-5" id="dsq-comment-124">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-124" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-124">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-124">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-124" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-124" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>The first one would simply be testing whether feigned humility is more persuasive as rhetoric.</p>
<p>The second one is more interesting to me&#8212;that sort of experiment would be difficult to set up but I&#8217;ll bet some smart behavioral/experimental economists/psychologists could come up with something clever.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-5" id="dsq-comment-190">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-190" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-190">
http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=750304864                <span id="dsq-author-user-190">Edward Hoefer</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-190" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-190" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Physicist Richard Feynman demonstrated meta-rational skills all the time. His ideas on Quantum Electrodynamics have been adopted and integrated into society. </p>
<p>Edgar Cayce also received widespread acceptance in society, yet over time the ideas of Feynman were contradicted less than those of Cayce, so today Feynman&#8217;s contributions are accepted and believed by far more than those of Cayce. Many of the people we consider to have contributed to society fall firmly in the camp of meta-rational thinkers. In fact, meta-rational thinkers are over represented in our collection of historical contributors over all disciplines.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even depth-4" id="dsq-comment-125">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-125" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-125">
http://elidourado.com/                <span id="dsq-author-user-125">Eli Dourado</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-125" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-125" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>If social systems have good feedback mechanisms, then those social systems will be better at getting good outcomes in spite of bad inputs. But that doesn&#8217;t have anything to do with how the accuracy of individual beliefs is influenced by meta-rationality.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-5" id="dsq-comment-128">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-128" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-128">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-128">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-128" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-128" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I wanted to make the argument that self-reflection can&#8217;t lead to accuracy, only trusting stories that are time-tested by good feedback mechanisms can. But I see now that that&#8217;s orthogonal to this discussion&#8211;you could simply argue that, if true, then a self-reflecting person would figure it out and start trusting said time-tested stories.</p>
<p>I guess my real claim is that cognitive biases are inescapable. Even if you are aware of them, you&#8217;re still human. I don&#8217;t know anyone who has ended up changing their priors on, say, economics issues, because they became aware of their own cognitive biases. But again&#8211;that may just be my own confirmation bias, since I believed in the weakness of human reason long before I learned about cognitive biases.</p>
<p>And when people do change their mind, it seems to have more in common mechanistically with a religious conversion than with a socratic dialogue. In other words, it happens for internal, emotional reasons, rather than because of some new evidence or a logical argument.</p>
<p>Anyway, food for thought. I don&#8217;t know that people that you would describe as meta-rational _aren&#8217;t_ more likely to be accurate, but I&#8217;m constrained by my priors and am unaware of the empirical evidence on the matter.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even depth-5" id="dsq-comment-131">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-131" class="dsq-comment-header">
