            <div id="dsq-comment-message-132" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>But there are a lot of priors involved in assessing new evidence, or what even is worth considering as evidence, no? Most interesting questions in economics are identification questions, which cannot truly be answered by data but rather must rely on some set of assumptions to interpret data. What is our criteria for selecting those assumptions, as individuals? I&#8217;m not sure there _is_ a rational criteria. If there is, I would be grateful to have it pointed out!</p>
</div>
