    <li class="comment odd alt depth-5" id="dsq-comment-189">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-189" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-189">
http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=750304864                <span id="dsq-author-user-189">Edward Hoefer</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-189" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-189" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Consistent use of the same subjective priors over time leads to either objective contradiction of some of those priors. Elements that are contradicted by experiment are discarded and the rest are retained. Consistent lack of experimental contraction builds confidence in subjective priors, but those priors cannot be considered fact, they just haven&#8217;t been contradicted yet. This is how scientific knowledge is accumulated. Most of what we know is wrong, we just haven&#8217;t been able to prove it yet.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even depth-5" id="dsq-comment-188">
