    <li class="comment odd alt depth-3" id="dsq-comment-991">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-991" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-991">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-991">Matt Sigl</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-991" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-991" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Take the process to its limits however and the only possible destination is madness. There are ALWAYS more priors to work through. That&#8217;s the nature of epistemology. That being said, understanding exactly where in the belief hierarchy you disagree with your opponent is the first step to understanding him. Most of the time we fight over issues at a level that disguises the real, higher level disagreements. In the end you get an entire country separated into red and blue states because the fundamental priors have bifurcated and we end up talking past each other. No one is really being &#8220;irrational&#8221; &#8230;most of the time.</p>
</div>
        </div>

