    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-122">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-122" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-122">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-122">Brock_C</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-122" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-122" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I have a friend who&#8217;s very good at finding truth. He&#8217;s taught me a lot. His technique is to actively seek out cognitive dissonance and then work like hell to understand how this new information might be correct in some way. I don&#8217;t know what &#8220;meta-rational&#8221; is really supposed to mean, but Matt (that&#8217;s my friend&#8217;s name) is mostly just open minded and emotionally non-defensive about his own views and priors.</p>
<p>Krugman does the opposite. Like a lot of very smart people, he&#8217;s pretty good at post hoc justifying positions he arrives at emotionally. At least, he&#8217;s &#8220;pretty good&#8221; if you only read his columns one at a time and don&#8217;t compare them to each other, or reality. But in a vacuum, it sounds convincing. Especially to him.</p>
</div>
        </div>

