    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-147">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-147" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-147">
http://ideophilus.wordpress.com/                <span id="dsq-author-user-147">Tim Makarios</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-147" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-147" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Doesn&#8217;t Aumann&#8217;s paper assume common knowledge of rationality?  If so, then a disagreement might let us conclude only that there is a failure of common knowledge of rationality, not necessarily of rationality itself.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-151">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-151" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-151">
http://elidourado.com/                <span id="dsq-author-user-151">Eli Dourado</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-151" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-151" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>My premise was that the macroeconomics literature and data are common knowledge. Even if you don&#8217;t want to go that far, there is a literature on the rationality of not having common priors. And even if you don&#8217;t want to go that far, Cowen and Hanson have you covered, because they discuss the &#8220;honesty&#8221; of disagreements more than the &#8220;rationality.&#8221;</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-3" id="dsq-comment-155">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-155" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-155">
http://ideophilus.wordpress.com/                <span id="dsq-author-user-155">Tim Makarios</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-155" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-155" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I was responding to your comment &#8220;If we have common “priors” and we are mutually aware of each others’ views, then if we do not agree ex post, at least one of us is being irrational.&#8221;  I&#8217;m not sure that Aumann&#8217;s paper lets us make this conclusion; we can only go as far as to say that we don&#8217;t have common knowledge of rationality.</p>
<p>And although I haven&#8217;t read their paper in detail, I&#8217;m not convinced that Cowen and Hanson aren&#8217;t also implicitly assuming common knowledge of some kind of rationality (or perhaps honesty).  How does exchanging my views with you help if I&#8217;m not sure that you&#8217;re honest?  Or if I&#8217;m not sure that you believe that I&#8217;m honest, I won&#8217;t conclude that you&#8217;re updating your beliefs based on what I tell you.  Or if I&#8217;m not sure that you believe that I&#8217;m completely convinced of your honesty &#8230;</p>
<p>Perhaps I&#8217;m wrong, but the result seems to require quite strong assumptions.  And therefore, taking the contrapositive, a failure to agree leads us to a very weak conclusion: that common knowledge of honesty or rationality doesn&#8217;t hold, not that honesty or rationality themselves must be absent on at least one side.</p>
</div>
        </div>

