    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-150">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-150" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-150">
http://twitter.com/Claudia_Sahm                <span id="dsq-author-user-150">Claudia Sahm</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-150" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-150" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>what makes you think these macroeconomic debates have anything to do with truth seeking? </p>
<p>macro policy is about getting us to a good place &#8230; the economic &#8216;promised land&#8217; of 2 percent inflation, 6 percent unemployment rate, a rising standard of living for all and sustainable long-term public debt. there is no global solution to that complex objective. there is state of the world in which each of our respected (and even some kooky) macro bloggers would be right. what the policy maker needs to do is find the local solutions that apply broadly or that seem most in line with current conditions. there are no guarantees that the truth does not morph into the untruth, so the focus is results and the contest is who can bring the most attention and strength to their argument. </p>
<p>but this is good&#8230;a robust, heated exchange of ideas is important. my beef is that this exchange often veers off from ideas and turns into a personality pro wrestling match. I don&#8217;t need meta-rational, self-effacing economists, I need intelligent, creative economists who are willing to push their ideas and push others in their ideas.</p>
</div>
        </div>

