    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-156">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-156" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-156">
http://foobarista.blogspot.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-156">foobarista</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-156" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-156" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>One other quality that is omitted in these sorts of discussions is what ye olden days referred to as wisdom.  The assumption behind these discussions is that all that matters is data + intellectual power, with an implication that everyone is a sort of computer and if fed the same inputs, equally intelligent people should spit out the same results.  </p>
<p>Wisdom is neither data nor intelligence; it&#8217;s a sort of negative knowledge rooted in history and life experience, with far more wisdom gained from carefully examined failure than by success.  This is why, frankly, people who&#8217;ve done nothing but succeed (either by skill or because they carefully avoided failure) are often extremely unwise, and often find ways to fail spectacularly when they finally do so.</p>
<p>The modern world dramatically undervalues wisdom, probably because of the rather mechanical approach to how people &#8220;think about thinking&#8221;. </p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
