    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-160">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-160" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-160">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-160">Greg van Paassen</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-160" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-160" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>This is the merest sophistry, and if you have summarised Cowen and Hanson&#8217;s paper correctly it is slipshod. So-called  &#8220;meta-rationality&#8221; is merely an appeal to authority dressed up in fancy language.</p>
<p>Truth-seekers base their opinions on their own assessments of the facts as they see them. The opinions of others may influence them to look again at the facts, but that&#8217;s all they should do.  Attempts to provide a partial ordering of intelligence are futile at best and normally harmful; an analytical framework that starts by assuming that such a thing exists and is relevant is poetry, not science.</p>
<p>A heuristic that I employ if if do not have the time to study contested problems in detail for myself is to look for the thinkers who emphasise the partiality and contingency of their understanding and solutions. </p>
<p>To take some of your points: no more sophisticated macro-economic model has had better predictive or prescriptive success than crude Keynesianism in situations such as the one that developed in 2007 and 2008.  Jeff Sachs may very well have argued at length, but he argued wrongly. Krugman has never said, for instance, that multipliers are stable.  By applying his &#8220;crude Keynesianism&#8221; description to Krugman Sachs merely betrays that either he has not read what Krugman wrote, or he does not understand simple English.</p>
<p>Sachs has a track record of creative misconstrual and caricature: ask Daron Acemoglu and James Robinson, or consult their blog for &#8220;Why Nations Fail.&#8221; There, too, Sachs betrays that his reading was at best superficial.  I can attest to this, having read the book.</p>
<p>Turning to Krugman&#8217;s dismissal of the libertarian and conservative blogosphere: an adequate criticism of his position would include examples of knowledge that Krugman should have had: predictions made that were more accurate than his own.  You provided nothing along these lines&#8211;no warrant at all, in fact&#8211;so your complaint amounts to saying that Krugman does not accept arguments from the authority of those blogs. We already knew that.</p>
<p>I take it back. This is not merely sophistry: it is juvenile sophistry.  Try to learn the difference between sophistry and rational argument; it will serve you well.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-197">
