        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-168" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-168" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>If he&#8217;s so brilliant, why hasn&#8217;t he figured out that he should be meta-rational?</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-171">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-171" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-171">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-171">ZuilSerip</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-171" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-171" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>An interesting perspective. Still, while I think you are correct in theory, there is an additional practicality that you must take into account: </p>
<p>Time is finite and the number of diverging opinions on internet is &#8211; for all practical purposes &#8211; infinite. While truly meta-rational actors would &#8211; in theory &#8211; carefully and honestly reconsider their perspectives and priors in light of every opposition, in practice this is completely impractical.</p>
<p>So what is a meta-rational actor to do?! The only reasonable course of action &#8211; to my mind &#8211; is to employ honest heuristics to prioritize whose diverging opinions you will devote some fraction of your limited time to honestly consider, and whose you will cursorily dismiss as a likely crack-pot. I propose that a reasonable such heuristic would be to triage the opinions of those who disagree with you based on the soundness of the arguments they&#8217;ve put forth in the past. (Even that is not sufficient, however, as no one has time to give everyone out there a chance to make a first impression &#8211; so we end up having to use proxies such as credentials and recommendations from known parties to further prioritize).</p>
<p>In any event, I agree that any reasonable person should consider Jeffery Sachs as one whose opposition should not be dismissed lightly. At the same time, I don&#8217;t blame Krugman from writing-off a large portion of the blogosphere off-hand.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="post pingback">
        <p>Pingback: <a href='http://onlytangentiallyrelated.wordpress.com/2013/03/15/is-paul-krugman-meta-meta-rational/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Is Paul Krugman Meta-Meta-Rational? &#8211; Only Tangentially Related</a></p>
    </li>
    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-174">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-174" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-174">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-174">Neel Krishnaswami</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-174" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-174" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Aumann&#8217;s theorem relies on Bayesian coherence, but Bayesian coherence requires  implausibly strong (in fact, provably too-strong) conditions to construct a Dutch Book. Specifically, the proof of Bayesian coherence requires that all propositions are subject to resolution through betting. </p>
<p>However, consider the law of the excluded middle. It is a purely logical axiom, and so evidence of the excluded middle (used to settle the bet) must be a deductive proof. (Since it is a theorem of classical logic, the axioms of probability theory imply it should have probability 1.) But there is no proof of it that does not already assume it (or something stronger) as an axiom! As a result, a constructive mathematician can reject the excluded middle, but you will still not be able to construct a Dutch book against her. Any proof of the excluded middle you offer her necessarily uses axioms she does not accept, and so you cannot offer mutually-acceptable evidence that the constructivist is wrong &#8212; the two of you will simply disagree about whether or not P or not-P holds for all P.</p>
<p>Ergo, persistent disagreement is in fact both possible and rational. (And meta-rational!)</p>
</div>
        </div>

