    <li class="comment odd alt depth-3" id="dsq-comment-237">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-237" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-237">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-237">Ari Lev</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-237" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-237" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>It appears that one doesn&#8217;t have to be humble to be meta-rational, though the given examples don&#8217;t show this, because it&#8217;s probably a rare situation.</p>
<p>Example: Person A and Person B disagree about the truth of statement X.  Person A believes X is false.  Person B believes X is true.  Person A and B have the exact same intelligence and information.  However, this disagreement is different from the examples above in that A and B share the same biases in support of X.  Person A could then conclude that she is more likely to be correct because she&#8217;s meta-rational.  She&#8217;s not being humble about her faults and admitting that her argument is possibly flawed because of her biases.  It fact, she might be bragging about how she&#8217;s so smart for accounting for her biases with made her come around to believe X to be false.</p>
<p>These arguments almost never occur though.  Even in cases of pre-apostates, it&#8217;s hard to argue that they come to the table with the same set of biases as non-pre-apostates.  No one probably shares the exact same set of relevant biases as someone else.  Perhaps there is a clearer distinction between humility and meta-rationality in the context of disagreements.  </p>
<p>Still, meta-rationality doesn&#8217;t appear to have to be about humility.</p>
<p>Meta-rationality might fall into the domain of common sense, but common sense is much broader.  Reminding someone &#8220;to have common sense&#8221; probably won&#8217;t inform the individual&#8217;s argumentation at that moment, even if they know of the meta-rationality flaw, because the term is too broad.  Therefore the &#8220;meta-rationality&#8221; serves a purpose.</p>
</div>
        </div>

