    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-218">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-218" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-218">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-218">Gaeranee</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-218" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-218" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>It could be that someone who is hyper meta rational became less so over time on a given topic because he has considered all possibilities and have eliminated the veracity of most of them through careful analysis; and therefore have arrived at the conclusion that only hypothesis 1 or 2 may be correct.  Now, it would seem that according to you, he is less meta rational than someone who is considering all 10 possibilities because the latter is more, self-doubting, humble and open-minded on the subject matter.  Or perhaps&#8230; he is just more self-doubting because he doesn&#8217;t know much about the subject matter.  So I can be meta rational on the topic of economics than Krugman?  That sounds comical because it leaves no room for progression of thought and the development of expertise over time.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t 100% agree with what Krugman writes just because I think economics is highly subjective and different situations call for different economic models.  I am also wary of people who have such strong politcal leanings because to me, they are idealogues.  And idealogues always have an agenda, which may taint their truth seeking abilities.  But I do hold the opinion of Krugman and other &#8220;experts&#8221; in high regard because he has obviously spent years studying economics more than I have.  </p>
<p>As for the whole line of reasoning that it&#8217;s better to make mistakes because you learn from them as opposed to people who succeed from the get go &#8212; I find this argument to be a bit bizarre.  Perhaps someone never made a mistake because he was highly self-doubting so he was more critical about different options; therefore, he made better judgments and became successful without making mistakes.  As a highly skeptical person, not just of other people but of myself as well and any data or philosophy, I may make less mistakes than people who aren&#8217;t self-doubting at all.  A meta rational person can learn through the mistakes of others rather than one&#8217;s own.</p>
</div>
        </div>

